===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|pytt||pit, hole in the ground, well, grave, pustule, pockmark}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*putjaz||pit, well}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|puteus||trench, pit, well}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*pewǝ-||to beat, hew}}. Cognate with {{etyl|fy|-}} {{m|fy|pet||pit}}, {{etyl|stq|-}} {{m|stq|put||pit}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{m|nl|put||well, pockmark}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{m|de|Pfütze||puddle, pool}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{m|da|pyt||pit}}, {{etyl|is|-}} {{m|is|pytt||pit}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[hole]] in the [[ground]].
# {{label|en|motor racing}} An area at a motor [[racetrack]] used for [[refuel]]ing and [[repair]]ing the vehicles during a race.
# {{label|en|music}} A section of the marching band containing [[mallet]] [[percussion]] instruments and other large percussion instruments too large to march, such as the [[tam tam]]. Also, the area on the [[sideline]]s where these instruments are placed.
# A [[mine]].
# {{label|en|archaeology}} A hole or [[trench]] in the ground, excavated according to [[grid]] coordinates, so that the [[provenance]] of any [[feature]] observed and any specimen or [[artifact]] revealed may be established by precise measurement.
# {{label|en|trading}} A [[trading pit]].
# {{label|en|in the plural|with ''the''|idiomatic|slang}} Something particularly unpleasant.
#: {{ux|en|His circus job was the '''pits''', but at least he was in show business.}}
# The [[bottom]] [[part]] of.
#: {{ux|en|I felt pain in the '''pit''' of my stomach.}}
# {{label|en|colloquial}} [[armpit|Armpit]].
# {{label|en|aviation}} A [[luggage hold]].
# {{label|en|countable}} A small surface hole or depression, a [[fossa]].
